<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 19 1990 v4 n7 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data base machines: agencies are turning to data base machines tohelp relieve system overloads.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Database machines are special processors designed to handledatabase inquiries and processing, removing database tasks fromthe host and running them on equipment optimized for the tasks.andO;Many relational DBMS users see database machines as a practicalalternative to buying more hardware when a mainframe-based DBMSstarts running short of memory.andP;  Computer Intelligence analystJerry Berry says database machines will be particularlycost-effective in applications requiring large amounts oftransactions.andP;  Database machine vendor ShareBase Corp VP ofMarketing Michael Reiff says the systems start saving users moneywhen the relational DBMS grows to between 1Gbyte and 2Gbytes.andP;  Thefederal market is expected to present more opportunities tovendors than the private sector; the Air Force ComputerAcquisition Center's Data Base Machine Requirements contract to beawarded in 1990 may be the largest order ever for databasemachines.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base ServersDedicated ProcessorsRelational DBMSLow CostUpgradingMainframe ComputersDistributed ProcessingMarket AnalysisGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>